WEBVTT

00:02.260 --> 00:08.960
This is a LibriVox recording. All LibriVox recordings are in the public domain. For more

00:08.960 --> 00:13.100
information on how to volunteer, please visit LibriVox.org.

00:13.200 --> 00:14.860
This is Jean O'Sullivan.

00:15.540 --> 00:18.860
The book is Treasure Island by Robert Louis Stevenson.

00:19.480 --> 00:24.300
This is Chapter 32, The Treasure Hunt, The Voice Among the Trees.

00:24.300 --> 00:29.740
Partly from the damping influence of this alarm, partly to rest silver in the sick folk,

00:30.160 --> 00:35.640
the whole party sat down as soon as they had gained the brow of the ascent. The plateau being

00:35.640 --> 00:41.480
somewhat tilted towards the west, this spot on which we had paused commanded a wide prospect on

00:41.480 --> 00:47.720
either hand. Before us, over the treetops, we beheld the cape of the woods, fringed with surf.

00:47.720 --> 00:54.820
Behind, we looked not only down upon the anchorage and skeleton island, but saw, clear across the

00:54.820 --> 01:01.220
spit and the eastern lowlands, a great field of open sea upon the east. Sheer above us rose the

01:01.220 --> 01:07.800
spyglass, here dotted with single pines, there black with precipices. There was no sound but

01:07.800 --> 01:14.160
that of the distant breakers mounting from all round, and the chirp of countless insects in the

01:14.160 --> 01:21.340
bush. Not a man, not a sail upon the sea. The very largeness of the view increased the sense of

01:21.340 --> 01:26.320
solitude. Silver, as he sat, took certain bearings with his compass.

01:27.420 --> 01:37.380
There are three tall trees, said he, about in the right line from skeleton island. Spyglass shoulder,

01:37.380 --> 01:45.180
I take it, means that lower point there. It's child's play to find the stuff now. I have half

01:45.180 --> 01:53.300
a mind to dine first. I don't feel sharp, growled Morgan, thinking a flint I think it were has done

01:53.300 --> 01:59.940
me. Ah, well, my son, if you praise your stars, he's dead, said Silver. You were an ugly devil,

02:00.460 --> 02:06.460
cried a third pirate with a shudder. That blew in the face, too. That was how the rum took him,

02:06.460 --> 02:12.980
added Mary. Blue. Well, I reckon he was blue. That's a true word. Ever since they had found

02:12.980 --> 02:18.380
the skeleton and got upon this train of thought, they had spoken lower and lower, and they almost

02:18.380 --> 02:23.720
had got to whispering by now, so that the sound of their talk hardly interrupted the silence of the

02:23.720 --> 02:30.460
wood. All of the sudden, out of the middle of the trees in front of us, a thin, high, trembling voice

02:30.460 --> 02:43.140
struck up the well-known air and words. I never have seen men more dreadfully affected than the

02:43.140 --> 02:48.000
pirates. The color went from their six faces like enchantment. Some leaped to their feet,

02:48.180 --> 02:54.300
some clawed hold of others. Morgan groveled on the ground. It's flint bike, cried Mary.

02:54.800 --> 02:59.140
The song had stopped as suddenly as it began. Broken off, you would have said, in the middle

02:59.140 --> 03:05.120
of a note, as though someone had laid his hand upon the singer's mouth. Coming through the clear,

03:05.280 --> 03:10.600
sunny atmosphere among the green treetops, I thought it had sounded airily and sweetly,

03:10.700 --> 03:16.500
and the effect on my companions was the stranger. Come, said Silver, struggling with his ashen lips

03:16.500 --> 03:24.840
to get the word out. This won't do. Stand by to go about. This is a rum start, and I can't name the

03:24.840 --> 03:32.000
but it's someone skylarking, someone that's flesh and blood, and you may lay to that.

03:32.460 --> 03:37.300
His courage had come back as he spoke, and some of the color to his face along with it.

03:37.780 --> 03:42.140
Already the others had begun to lend an ear to this encouragement and were coming a little to

03:42.140 --> 03:48.220
themselves when the same voice broke out again, not this time singing, but in a faint, distant

03:48.220 --> 03:52.140
that echoed yet fainter among the clefts of the spyglass.

03:53.140 --> 03:58.260
Darby McGraw, it wailed, for that is the word that best describes the sound.

03:58.400 --> 04:04.680
Darby McGraw, Darby McGraw. Again and again, and then rising a little higher,

04:04.960 --> 04:09.420
and with an oath that I leave out. Fetch after the rum, Darby.

04:10.520 --> 04:16.280
The buccaneers remained rooted to the ground, their eyes starting from their heads. Long after

04:16.280 --> 04:22.320
voice had died away, they still stared in silence, dreadfully before them.

04:22.720 --> 04:25.440
That fixes it, gasped one. Let's go.

04:26.160 --> 04:32.160
They were his last words, moaned Morgan. His last words above board.

04:33.080 --> 04:37.940
Dick had his Bible out and was praying volubly. He had been well brought up,

04:38.040 --> 04:41.200
had Dick, before he came to see and fell among bad companions.

04:41.800 --> 04:46.360
Still, Silver was unconquered. I could hear his teeth rattle in his head,

04:46.800 --> 04:48.280
but he had not yet surrendered.

04:49.940 --> 04:53.940
Nobody in this here island ever heard of Darby, he muttered.

04:54.300 --> 04:56.660
Not one, but us that's here.

04:57.260 --> 05:00.340
And then, making a great effort, shipmates, he cried.

05:00.920 --> 05:04.820
I'm here to get that stuff and I'll not be beat by man or devil.

05:05.200 --> 05:09.120
I never was a fear to flint in his life and by the powers I'll face him dead.

05:09.120 --> 05:13.040
There's seven hundred thousand pound, not a quarter mile from here.

05:13.380 --> 05:17.460
When did ever a gentleman of fortune show his stern to that much dollars

05:17.460 --> 05:21.280
for a boozy old seaman with a blue mug and him dead too?

05:21.920 --> 05:25.020
But there was no sign of reawakening courage in his followers,

05:25.480 --> 05:29.140
rather indeed of growing terror at the irreverence of his words.

05:30.580 --> 05:34.140
Belay there, John, said Mary. Don't you cross a spirit?

05:35.020 --> 05:37.780
And the rest were all too terrified to reply.

05:37.780 --> 05:42.020
They would have run away severally had they dared, but fear kept them together

05:42.020 --> 05:45.820
and kept them close by John as if his daring helped them.

05:46.020 --> 05:49.280
He, on his part, had pretty well fought his weakness down.

05:50.360 --> 05:56.160
Spirit? Well, maybe, he said, but there's one thing not clear to me.

05:56.620 --> 06:02.160
There was an echo. Now no man ever seen a spirit with a shadow.

06:02.540 --> 06:04.440
Well, then what's he doing with an echo to him?

06:04.440 --> 06:08.160
I should like to know. That ain't in nature, surely.

06:09.360 --> 06:13.660
This argument seemed weak enough to me, but you can never tell what will affect the

06:13.660 --> 06:17.700
superstitious. And to my wonder, George Mary was greatly relieved.

06:18.560 --> 06:23.040
Well, that's so, he said. You have a head upon your shoulders, John, and no mistake.

06:23.440 --> 06:28.340
Bouch, shipmates. This here crew is on a wrong tack, I do believe, and come to think of it.

06:28.340 --> 06:35.020
It was like Flint's voice, I grant you, but not just so clear away like it after all.

06:35.300 --> 06:40.540
It was like her somebody else's voice now. It was like her by the powers.

06:41.000 --> 06:43.120
Ben Gunn, roared Silver.

06:44.360 --> 06:48.940
Aye, and so it were, cried Morgan, springing on his knees.

06:49.360 --> 06:50.910
Ben Gunn, it were.

06:51.860 --> 06:55.560
It don't make much odds do it now, asked Dick.

06:55.560 --> 06:59.120
Ben Gunn's not here in the body any more than Flint.

07:00.040 --> 07:03.000
But the older hands greeted this remark with scorn.

07:03.840 --> 07:08.780
Why, nobody minds Ben Gunn, cried Mary. Dead or alive, nobody minds him.

07:09.720 --> 07:14.880
It was extraordinary how their spirits had returned and how the natural color had revived

07:14.880 --> 07:19.120
in their faces. Soon they were chatting together, with intervals of listening,

07:19.160 --> 07:23.700
and not long after, hearing no further sound, they shouldered the tools and set forth again,

07:23.700 --> 07:28.780
Mary walking first with Silver's compass to keep them on the right line with Skeleton Island.

07:29.280 --> 07:35.880
He had said the truth, dead or alive, nobody minded Ben Gunn. Dick alone still held his Bible

07:35.880 --> 07:40.700
and looked around him as he went, with fearful glances, but he found no sympathy,

07:41.140 --> 07:43.760
and Silver even joked him on his precautions.

07:45.880 --> 07:52.880
I told you, said he, I told you he had spoiled your Bible. If it ain't no good to swear by,

07:52.880 --> 07:58.060
what do you suppose a spirit would give for it? Not that! And he snapped his big fingers,

07:58.400 --> 08:04.280
halting a moment on his crutch. But Dick was not to be comforted. Indeed, it was soon plain to me

08:04.280 --> 08:09.520
that the lad was falling sick, hastened by heat, exhaustion, and the shock of his alarm,

08:09.840 --> 08:14.220
the fever predicted by Dr. Livesey was evidently growing swiftly higher.

08:14.980 --> 08:21.240
It was fine, open, walking here upon the summit. Our way lay a little downhill, for,

08:21.240 --> 08:27.600
as I have said, the plateau tilted toward the west. The pines, great and small, grew wide apart,

08:27.860 --> 08:33.420
and even between the clumps of nutmeg and azalea, wide open spaces baked in the hot sunshine.

08:33.940 --> 08:39.580
Striking as we did, pretty near northwest across the island, we drew, on the one hand,

08:39.640 --> 08:45.120
ever nearer under the shoulders of the spyglass, and on the other, looked ever wider over that

08:45.120 --> 08:50.920
western bay where I had once tossed and trembled in the oracle. The first of the tall trees was

08:50.920 --> 08:56.640
reached, and by the bearings proved the wrong one, so with the second. The third rose nearly

08:56.640 --> 09:02.540
two hundred feet into the air above a clump of underwood, a giant of a vegetable with a red

09:02.540 --> 09:07.800
column as big as a cottage, and a wide shadow around in which a company could have maneuvered.

09:07.860 --> 09:14.060
It was conspicuous far to see both on the east and west, and might have been entered as a sailing

09:14.060 --> 09:19.200
mark upon the chart. But it was not its size that now impressed my companions. It was the

09:19.200 --> 09:24.640
knowledge that seven hundred thousand pounds in gold lay somewhere buried below its spreading

09:24.640 --> 09:30.280
shadow. The thought of the money as they drew nearer swallowed up their previous terrors,

09:30.600 --> 09:37.000
their eyes burned in their heads, their feet grew speedier and lighter, their whole soul was found

09:37.000 --> 09:43.280
up in that fortune, that whole lifetime of extravagance and pleasure that lay waiting there

09:43.280 --> 09:49.800
for each of them. Silver hobbled, grunting on his crutch, his nostrils stood out and quivered. He

09:49.800 --> 09:54.980
cursed like a madman when the flies settled on his hot and shiny countenance. He plucked furiously at

09:54.980 --> 10:00.060
the line that held me to him, and from time to time turned his eyes upon me with a deadly look.

10:00.700 --> 10:07.040
Certainly he took no pains to hide his thoughts, and certainly I read them like print. In the

10:07.040 --> 10:12.480
immediate nearness of the gold all else had been forgotten. His promise and the doctor's warning

10:12.480 --> 10:17.440
were both things of the past, and I could not doubt that he hoped to seize upon the treasure,

10:17.940 --> 10:23.440
find and board the Hispaniola under cover of night, cut every honest throat about that island,

10:23.540 --> 10:30.440
and sail away as he had first intended, laden with crimes and riches. Shaken as I was with

10:30.440 --> 10:34.880
these alarms, it was hard for me to keep up with the rapid pace of the treasure hunters.

10:35.420 --> 10:40.520
Now and again I stumbled, and it was then that Silver plucked so roughly at the rope and launched

10:40.520 --> 10:45.700
at me his murderous glances. Dick, who had dropped behind us and now brought up the rear,

10:45.800 --> 10:51.880
was babbling to himself, both prayers and curses as his fever kept rising. This also added to my

10:51.880 --> 10:57.360
wretchedness, and to crown it all I was haunted by the thought of the tragedy that had once been

10:57.360 --> 11:03.460
acted on that plateau, when that ungodly buccaneer with the blue face, he who died at Savannah,

11:03.640 --> 11:10.080
singing and shouting for a drink, had there, with his own hand, cut down his six accomplices.

11:10.080 --> 11:16.660
This grove that was now so peaceful must then have rung with cries, I thought, and even with

11:16.660 --> 11:23.080
the thought I could believe I heard it ringing still. We were now at the margin of the thicket.

11:24.360 --> 11:29.220
Huzzah mates, all together! shouted Mary, and the foremost broke into a run, and suddenly,

11:29.360 --> 11:35.840
not ten yards further, we beheld them stop. A low cry arose. Silver doubled his pace,

11:35.840 --> 11:41.320
digging away with the foot of his crutch like one possessed, and next moment he and I had come also

11:41.320 --> 11:49.100
to a dead halt. Before us was a great excavation, not very recent, for the sides had fallen in and

11:49.100 --> 11:55.380
grass had sprouted on the bottom. In this were the shaft of a pick broken in two and the boards of

11:55.380 --> 12:01.940
several packing cases strewn around. On one of these boards I saw, branded with a hot iron,

12:01.940 --> 12:09.160
the name Walrus, the name of Flint's ship. All was clear to probation.

12:09.860 --> 12:16.500
The cash had been found and rifled. The seven hundred thousand pounds were gone.

12:18.500 --> 12:23.380
End of chapter 32. This is Jean O'Sullivan for LibriVox.

